{
  "Which branch of biology studies animals?": "",
  "Microbiology": "",
  "Botany": "",
  "Ecology": "",
  "Zoology": "",
  "Zoology is the branch of biology dedicated to the study of animals. Botany studies plants, microbiology studies microscopic organisms, and ecology studies organisms and their environment.": "",
  "Which branch of biology studies plants?": "",
  "Anatomy": "",
  "Genetics": "",
  "Botany is the study of plants — everything from tiny mosses to giant redwoods. It includes plant structure, growth, reproduction, and classification.": "",
  "A scientist studies bacteria, viruses, and fungi that are too small to see without a microscope. This field is called:": "",
  "Cell biology": "",
  "Physiology": "",
  "Microbiology is the study of microscopic organisms — bacteria, viruses, fungi, and protists. Cell biology studies cell structure in general, while anatomy focuses on body structures.": "",
  "The study of heredity and how traits are passed from parents to offspring is called:": "",
  "Biochemistry": "",
  "Genetics is the study of genes, heredity, and genetic variation. It explains why children resemble their parents and how traits are inherited.": "",
  "Which branch of biology studies how organisms interact with each other and their environment?": "",
  "Ecology studies the relationships between organisms and their environment — including food webs, ecosystems, and how species interact with each other.": "",
  "The study of body structures (like bones, muscles, and organs) is called:": "",
  "Anatomy is the study of the STRUCTURE of organisms. It describes what things look like and where they are. Physiology, by contrast, studies how structures FUNCTION.": "",
  "Physiology is the study of:": "",
  "Microscopic organisms": "",
  "The shape and structure of body parts": "",
  "Fossils and ancient life": "",
  "How the body and its parts function": "",
  "Physiology studies how organs and body systems WORK. For example, how the heart pumps blood, how lungs exchange gases, or how muscles generate force. Anatomy studies the structure, not the function.": "",
  "Cell biology focuses on:": "",
  "The structure and function of cells": "",
  "Only plant cells": "",
  "The classification of animals": "",
  "How organisms interact with their environment": "",
  "Cell biology studies the structure, function, and behavior of cells — the basic unit of life. It covers all types of cells (plant, animal, bacterial), not just one kind.": "",
  "Biochemistry is the study of:": "",
  "The classification of organisms": "",
  "How diseases spread through populations": "",
  "The behavior of animals in the wild": "",
  "The chemical processes and substances in living things": "",
  "Biochemistry combines biology and chemistry to study the chemical reactions and molecules (proteins, DNA, lipids, carbohydrates) that are essential to life.": "",
  "What is the key difference between anatomy and physiology?": "",
  "Anatomy studies cells; physiology studies organs": "",
  "Anatomy studies animals; physiology studies plants": "",
  "There is no difference — they are the same field": "",
  "Anatomy studies structure; physiology studies function": "",
  "Anatomy = what it looks like (structure). Physiology = how it works (function). They complement each other — you can't fully understand an organ without knowing both its structure and how it functions.": "",
  "What is 'zoology'?": "",
  "The study of plants in zoo gardens": "",
  "The branch of biology that studies animals": "",
  "The study of microscopic organisms": "",
  "The study of zoos and captive animals only": "",
  "Zoology (from Greek 'zoon' = animal) is the study of all animals — not just zoo animals. It includes animal behavior, physiology, classification, and evolution.": "",
  "What is 'botany'?": "",
  "The study of body structures": "",
  "The study of robots in biology": "",
  "The study of ocean organisms": "",
  "The branch of biology that studies plants": "",
  "Botany is the study of plants — their structure, growth, reproduction, metabolism, diseases, and classification. Botanists study everything from algae to flowering trees.": "",
  "What is 'microbiology'?": "",
  "The study of microscopic organisms including bacteria, viruses, and fungi": "",
  "The study of microchips in medical devices": "",
  "The study of cells only in plants": "",
  "The study of very small animals": "",
  "Microbiology studies organisms too small to see without a microscope — bacteria, viruses, fungi, protists, and some algae. It's crucial for medicine, food safety, and environmental science.": "",
  "What is 'genetics'?": "",
  "The study of genius-level intelligence": "",
  "The study of general biology topics": "",
  "The study of heredity and the variation of inherited characteristics": "",
  "The study of animal behavior": "",
  "Genetics is the study of genes, DNA, and how traits are inherited from parents to offspring. It explains genetic variation, hereditary diseases, and how organisms evolve.": "",
  "What is 'ecology'?": "",
  "The study of interactions among organisms and their environment": "",
  "The study of ancient ecosystems from fossils": "",
  "The study of economic systems": "",
  "The same thing as environmentalism or recycling": "",
  "Ecology is the scientific study of how organisms interact with each other and their physical environment. While ecology can INFORM environmentalism, they are not the same thing — ecology is science, environmentalism is activism.": "",
  "What does 'anatomy' study?": "",
  "The evolution of species over time": "",
  "The structure and form of organisms and their parts": "",
  "How body parts function": "",
  "Chemical reactions inside cells": "",
  "Anatomy studies the physical structure of organisms — where things are located and what they look like. How those structures work is physiology.": "",
  "What does 'physiology' study?": "",
  "The names and locations of body parts": "",
  "The physical fitness of athletes": "",
  "The functions and mechanisms of living organisms and their parts": "",
  "How to classify organisms into groups": "",
  "Physiology studies how organisms and their parts WORK — heart pumping, nerve signaling, digestion, etc. Naming body parts is anatomy, grouping organisms is taxonomy.": "",
  "What does 'biochemistry' study?": "",
  "The chemical processes and molecules in living organisms": "",
  "The behavior of organisms in chemical labs": "",
  "The biography of famous chemists": "",
  "Only inorganic chemical reactions": "",
  "Biochemistry is the intersection of biology and chemistry — it studies the chemical reactions, enzymes, proteins, lipids, carbohydrates, and nucleic acids that make life possible.": "",
  "What does 'cell biology' focus on?": "",
  "The structure, function, and behavior of cells": "",
  "Only the cells of animals": "",
  "The environment where cells live in nature": "",
  "Prison cells and their biology": "",
  "Cell biology studies cells — the basic units of life. It examines cell structure, organelles, cell division, communication, and how cells function. It covers ALL cell types: animal, plant, bacterial, and more.": "",
  "What is 'taxonomy'?": "",
  "The science of classifying and naming organisms": "",
  "The study of taxes on biological products": "",
  "A type of microscope": "",
  "The study of how organisms move": "",
  "Taxonomy is the branch of science that classifies organisms into groups based on shared characteristics. It gives organisms scientific names (like Homo sapiens for humans) and organizes them into kingdoms, phyla, classes, orders, families, genera, and species.": "",
  "A researcher spends her career studying how wheat, rice, and corn can be bred to resist drought. She analyzes leaf stomata, root absorption, and photosynthetic efficiency. Which branch of biology best describes her specialty?": "",
  "Botany — she studies plant structures and functions": "",
  "Microbiology — she uses microscopes to study stomata": "",
  "Ecology — she studies plants in the environment": "",
  "Zoology — she works on a farm with animals": "",
  "Her focus is entirely on plants (wheat, rice, corn) and their structures (stomata, roots, photosynthesis). That's botany. Even though she might work on a farm, the organisms she studies are plants, not animals. Using a microscope doesn't make it microbiology — it's the subject (microscopic organisms) that defines microbiology.": "",
  "Dr. Park studies how wolves affect elk populations, which in turn affects plant growth along rivers in Yellowstone. She is studying a complex chain of interactions. Which branch of biology is this?": "",
  "Ecology — she studies interactions between organisms and their environment": "",
  "Genetics — she studies inherited traits in wolves": "",
  "Botany — she studies plant growth": "",
  "Zoology — she studies wolves and elk": "",
  "This is a trophic cascade — wolves affect elk, which affect plants. The study of these multi-species interactions and how they reshape the environment is ecology. While wolves and elk are animals (zoology) and plants are involved (botany), the focus on interspecies INTERACTIONS and ecosystem effects makes it ecology.": "",
  "A hospital lab technician identifies the specific strain of bacteria causing a patient's infection by culturing it, examining it under a microscope, and testing its antibiotic sensitivity. Which branch of biology is MOST relevant to her work?": "",
  "Anatomy — she examines structures under a microscope": "",
  "Biochemistry — she tests chemicals (antibiotics)": "",
  "Microbiology — she studies and identifies microscopic organisms": "",
  "Genetics — she identifies the strain (genetic information)": "",
  "Her primary work is identifying and studying bacteria — microscopic organisms. That's microbiology. While she does examine structures (anatomy), test chemicals (biochemistry), and identify strains (genetics), the central focus on identifying pathogenic microorganisms makes microbiology the most relevant branch.": "",
  "Two siblings have different eye colors despite having the same parents. A biology student wants to understand why. Which branch of biology would BEST explain this?": "",
  "Genetics — it explains how traits are inherited and vary between siblings": "",
  "Anatomy — it describes what eyes look like": "",
  "Ecology — siblings interact in the same environment": "",
  "Physiology — it explains how eyes function": "",
  "Different eye colors in siblings are caused by different combinations of genes inherited from their parents. Genetics explains how alleles for eye color are passed on and why siblings can end up with different combinations. Anatomy describes eye structure, physiology describes how eyes work, but neither explains inheritance patterns.": "",
  "A student dissects a frog and labels each organ: heart, liver, lungs, stomach, and kidneys. She draws detailed diagrams of their shapes and positions. She is practicing:": "",
  "Ecology — she is studying the frog in its environment": "",
  "Anatomy — she is studying the structure and position of organs": "",
  "Physiology — she is studying how the organs work": "",
  "Zoology — she is studying an animal": "",
  "She is labeling, drawing, and mapping organ STRUCTURES and POSITIONS — that's anatomy. If she measured how fast the heart pumps or how the kidneys filter blood, that would be physiology. While the frog is an animal (zoology), her specific activity (dissection and structural labeling) is anatomy.": "",
  "A scientist studies how enzymes in the stomach break down proteins into amino acids using hydrochloric acid. This work combines biology with chemistry. Which branch is she working in?": "",
  "Anatomy — she studies the stomach": "",
  "Cell biology — she studies what happens inside cells": "",
  "Physiology — she studies how digestion works": "",
  "Biochemistry — she studies chemical processes in living things": "",
  "Her focus is on the CHEMICAL processes (enzyme reactions, HCl, protein breakdown) in a biological system. That's biochemistry. While physiology also covers digestion, the emphasis on molecular-level chemical reactions specifically places this in biochemistry.": "",
  "A new disease is killing honey bee colonies around the world. Research teams are formed — some study the virus causing it, some study how it spreads through hives, and some study how bee decline affects pollination of crops. Which statement BEST describes this situation?": "",
  "Only ecology matters because it affects ecosystems": "",
  "Biology branches never overlap — each team works in isolation": "",
  "Multiple branches of biology (microbiology, ecology, botany) work together to solve complex problems": "",
  "Only microbiology is needed because it's caused by a virus": "",
  "Real-world biological problems rarely fit neatly into one branch. Studying the virus = microbiology. Studying spread through hives = ecology and zoology. Studying pollination impact = botany and ecology. Modern biology is highly interdisciplinary — branches frequently overlap and collaborate.": "",
  "A forensic scientist analyzes DNA from blood found at a crime scene to identify a suspect. Her work draws MOST heavily from which two branches of biology?": "",
  "Genetics and biochemistry — she uses DNA analysis and molecular techniques": "",
  "Zoology and anatomy — she studies human body parts": "",
  "Ecology and botany — she studies the environment of the crime scene": "",
  "Microbiology and physiology — she studies the blood's microbes": "",
  "DNA analysis is fundamentally genetics (studying genetic variation between individuals) combined with biochemistry (the molecular techniques used to extract, amplify, and sequence DNA). These two branches form the backbone of forensic biology.": "",
  "A student says: 'Anatomy and physiology are basically the same thing.' Why is this statement INCORRECT?": "",
  "Anatomy uses microscopes; physiology does not": "",
  "Anatomy studies STRUCTURE (what it looks like); physiology studies FUNCTION (how it works)": "",
  "The student is actually correct — they are the same": "",
  "Anatomy is only for humans; physiology is for all organisms": "",
  "Anatomy describes the structure, shape, and position of body parts (what the heart looks like, where it's located). Physiology describes how those parts function (how the heart pumps blood, how valves open and close). Both fields apply to all organisms, not just humans, and both can use microscopes.": "",
  "A marine biologist studies dolphins, ocean algae, deep-sea bacteria, and coral reef ecosystems. A student says marine biology is 'just zoology because it studies dolphins.' Why is this WRONG?": "",
  "The student is correct — marine biology IS a subset of zoology": "",
  "Dolphins are not animals, so it's not zoology": "",
  "Marine biology only studies fish, not dolphins": "",
  "Marine biology spans multiple branches (zoology, botany, microbiology, ecology) — it's defined by environment (ocean), not organism type": "",
  "Marine biology is defined by its ENVIRONMENT (ocean/saltwater), not by one type of organism. It includes studying ocean animals (zoology), ocean plants and algae (botany), ocean bacteria (microbiology), and ocean ecosystems (ecology). This cross-branch scope makes it a distinct field, not just a subset of zoology.": ""
}